workaround ICD9-Code V12.54

(16.01.2017) ICD9 code V12.54 “Personal history of transient ischemic attack” workaround:

This ICD9 code indicates a prevalence in the main-comorb. category “Stroke.IschemAttack”. In some cases, if this code appears with an IXDAY >180, then the “personal history” will be flagged as an incidence due to that. To be more exact: This happens when this is the only ICD9 code within this category which appears at a indexdate later than 180, which in origin defines an incident diagnosis. So this has to be handled with care to avoid false-positive incidence flag for “Stroke.IschemAttack”. To fix that, from a conservative standpoint, every patient which has an ICD9 V12.54 event at an Indexdate >=180, the indexdate will be change to a pre-incident date x. Therefore none V12.54 event will be handled as an incident. For the moment x will be set to 179. One could also set x <= 30. If this would be the case, than that will be considered for the expanded medical history, which is defined as every event with an indexdate <= 30. But this would assume, that if V12.54 would appear at an indexdate >=180, that this would be similar to an indexdate <= 30. This would be a too strong assumption from my standpoint, if there are no further information or ideas which would support an <= 30 approach.

It is important to consider occurrence of a treatment in the same observation which IXDAY will be fixed in that way. Because some observations include both: treatment and diagnosis events. To avoid a mistake by an accidently changing the indexdate of a treatment event, every observation containing V12.54 and containing a treatment has to be copied to save the treatment information. To be more precise: A) One copy to patch the V12.54 events - without any treatment information B) Another copy without V12.54 events - with treatment information only

Step-by-step: 1) get all V12.54 observations from origin table 2) delete all V12.54 observations from origin table 3) Make copy A) and B) as mentioned above 4) attach A) and B) to origin table

The Truven Health MarketScan® Databases Insurance classes:

The Truven Health MarketScan Databases consist of several different datasets. The Commercial Claims and Encounters (CCAE) database is a nationally representative collection of inpatient, outpatient, and pharmaceutical claims from more than 200 insurance carriers and large, self-insuring companies. The Medicare Supplemental and Coordination of Benefits (MDCR) database consists of claims for Medicare-eligible retirees with employer-sponsored supplemental plans.
